history.content:
Don't really need EE120.

All you really need for 106a is physics and basic linear algebra/multi-var, along with ability to code in python. 

---------------

I tell students that you need:

1. Highschool physics (or 7A)

2. Programming to the level of 61B (python is a plus but not required)

3. Linear Algebra to the level of 16A/B

4. The maturity to take an upper div

120 is totally unnecessary and is only there because it's really annoying to change anything on those pages (you have to deal with the academic senate...)

Don't really need EE120.

All you really need for 106a is physics and basic linear algebra/multi-var, along with ability to code in python.

How necessary is the prereq of EE120 (Signals) for this course? I found a copy of its course syllabus from one of its past years and it stated all that was need as a prereq was knowledge of linear algebra (which i have through EE16a/b/ Math 54), calculus (which i have from Math 53), physics (which I have from Physics 7A/b), and Python programming (which I have from CS61a).

Would it be a terrible idea to not take EE120 and take this course? Or is EE120 more of an unofficial prereq? Thanks!
